                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     CRICKET BRIEFS
        ICC to meet on Thursday  New Delhi: The International Cricket Council (ICC) executive board will have a teleconference on Thursday to decide whether the Champions Trophy would stay in Pakistan or be shifted to some where else.  ldquo;Yes, the telephone hook-up of the ICC directors is on Thursday, rdquo; an ICC spokesman said.  Earlier on Sunday, the teams were briefed about the security arrangements in Pakistan.
  Though the successful hosting of the Asia Cup did brighten Pakistan rsquo;s chances of hosting the biennial event, players from Australia, New Zealand, England and South Africa are still cagey about the security situation in the volatile country.   Confusion  Calcutta: There seems to be some confusion over the nomination papers filed by Subhasish Sarkar for one of the vice-president rsquo;s posts from the districts, says A Staff Reporter. Apparently his papers hasn rsquo;t been signed by the district magistrate and cleared by the Malda DSA.  It is now almost certain that the elections will be held under the supervision of an observer. The ruling group won rsquo;t oppose when the case comes up for hearing at a city civil court on Thursday.  Meanwhile, Adrian le Roux conducted the first day rsquo;s fitness camp for Bengal probables at the Eden on Tuesday.  ECB stand  Dubai: The ICC and the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) on Tuesday reaffirmed their support for mandatory release of associate players from the counties to take part in international matches and the priority of Future Tours Programme (FTP).
  The decision followed discussions between ICC president David Morgan and new ICC chief executive officer Haroon Lorgat with the ECB chairman Giles Clarke and chief executive David Collier.  BCCI waits  Mumbai: The cricket board is yet to receive application forms from the government for sending its recommendations for this year rsquo;s Arjuna awards, BCCI sources said on Tuesday.  As per the normal course, BCCI receives the application forms from the government and then decides whom to recommend for the Arjuna awards, they said.  WI squad  Bridgetown: West Indies captain Chris Gayle was among 17 internationals selected in the 32-man Stanford Superstars training squad for the $20 million Twenty20 match against England in November. Shivnarine Chanderpaul, Ramnaresh Sarwan, Jerome Taylor and Dwayne Bravo were also picked in the squad on late Monday for the November match in Antigua.  Texan billionaire Allen Stanford will spend $100 million on five Twenty20 matches over five years. 
                                                                                                                                                               
